# Backend Rules

## 1. File Structure

### 1.1 Module folder structure

Every feature module MUST follow this exact structure. No exceptions.

```
modules/
└── <feature>/
    ├── index.ts                 barrel — re-exports router + service (+ util only if file exists); see §1.2
    ├── <feature>.router.ts      routes only — FastifyPluginAsync
    ├── <feature>.controller.ts  HTTP layer — calls service, sends reply
    ├── <feature>.service.ts     business logic — no HTTP concepts (public API for other modules)
    ├── <feature>.util.ts        optional — add only when needed; never scaffold empty (see §1.2)
    ├── <feature>.error.ts       Error Classes extended from `AppError`
    └── internal/
        ├── <feature>.entity.ts     TypeORM entity
        ├── <feature>.repository.ts Repository file for task
        ├── <feature>.serializer.ts Serializer for task
        ├── <feature>.reader.ts     DB Read operations
        └── <feature>.writer.ts     DB write operations
```

### 1.2 Module barrel file (`index.ts`)

Every feature module MUST have `index.ts` at the module root. It re-exports the **public** surface only:

1. **From `<feature>.router.ts`** — export the route registration artifact (e.g. `{feature}RouteConfig`) that `routers.ts` needs.
2. **From `<feature>.service.ts`** — export the service (named or default re-export, matching how the service file exports).
3. **From `<feature>.util.ts`** — export util symbols **only when that file exists**. If there is no util file, do **not** add util exports or a stub util file.

**`<feature>.util.ts`:** create it **only when there is a concrete requirement** (e.g. pure helpers shared with other modules, or logic worth splitting from the service). Do **not** generate an empty `<feature>.util.ts` when adding a new module “by default”.

```ts
// index.ts — example when util exists
export { taskRouteConfig } from "./task.router";
export { default as TaskService } from "./task.service";
export { formatTaskLabel, slugifyTaskName } from "./task.util";

// index.ts — example when util does NOT exist (no util file, no util line)
export { taskRouteConfig } from "./task.router";
export { default as TaskService } from "./task.service";
```

Other modules may import from `@modules/<feature>` for the route config and cross-module service/util access, as long as those symbols are listed here (see §11.2).

### 1.3 Registering a new module

Each module MUST export a `{feature}RouteConfig: RouterConfig` from its router file (or re-export it from `index.ts` per §1.2).
Only ever touch ONE file when adding a new module — `src/routers.ts`.
`routers.ts` ONLY imports route configs and assembles them into `routerConfigs` — no inline `{ endpoint, router }` objects.
Never edit `app.ts`, `data-source.ts`, `db-config.ts`, `error-handler.ts` to add a new module.

```ts
// <feature>.router.ts — export route config
export const taskRouteConfig: RouterConfig = {
  endpoint: "/tasks",
  router: taskRouter,
};

// routers.ts — import configs only (from module barrel)
import { taskRouteConfig } from "@modules/task";

export const routerConfigs: RouterConfig[] = [
  healthRouteConfig,
  authRouteConfig,
  userRouteConfig,
  taskRouteConfig, // ← add here
];
```

### 1.4 Plugin folder structure

```
plugins/
├── cors.plugin.ts
├── error.plugin.ts
├── helmet.plugin.ts
├── jwt.plugin.ts
└── request-context.plugin.ts
```

