## 11. Import Rules

### 11.1 Always use path aliases for cross-folder imports

Available aliases:
@lib/_ → src/lib/_
@modules/_ → src/modules/_
@plugins/_ → src/plugins/_
@middleware/_ → src/middleware/_
@config/_ → src/config/_
@server/_ → src/server/_

Cross-folder imports MUST use aliases — never relative paths:

```ts
// ✓ correct — alias
import { successResponse } from "@lib/api-response";
import { requireAuth } from "@middleware/require-auth";
import AppDataSource from "@database/data-source";

// ✗ wrong — relative cross-folder
import { successResponse } from "../../lib/api-response";
import { requireAuth } from "../../../middleware/require-auth";
import { NotFoundException } from "../../exceptions/http.exception";
```

Same-folder imports stay relative — do not use aliases within the same module:

```ts
// ✓ correct — same folder stays relative for service/router/controller
import { AuthService } from "./auth.service";
// ✓ schemas and data types come from packages/shared, not ./auth.schema or ./auth.types
import { signinSchema } from "@task-forge/shared/schemas";
import type { SigninInput } from "@task-forge/shared/types";

// ✗ wrong — alias for same folder
import { AuthService } from "@modules/auth/auth.service";
```

### 11.2 Cross-module imports (other features)

When importing from **another** feature under `modules/`, you may import **only** that feature’s `<feature>.service.ts` and `<feature>.util.ts` (if it exists). Do not import that feature’s `internal/` folder, router, controller, prehandlers, or other private files.

```ts
// ✓ correct
import TaskService from "@modules/task/task.service";
import { computeSlug } from "@modules/task/task.util";

// ✗ wrong — another module’s internal layer is private
import { TaskReader } from "@modules/task/internal/task.reader";
```

